{{Refnotes|date=November 2019}} '''Kadenokōji Family''' (勘解由小路家) is one of the [[clans]] of Japan.
This [[family name]] ({{ill|surname|ja|名字|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/surname|qq=}}) with five kanji characters is, alongside the [[Saemon Saburō]] surname from [[Saitama Prefecture]], one of the longest surnames in Japan. Excluding family names introduced through [[naturalization]] in modern times{{Refnest|For example, former sumo wrestler [[Hakuhō Shō]] took on the Japanese name of Mangaraja Jarub Ananda upon naturalization. While not native to Japan, this technically introduces a family name, "Mangarajajarub," into Japanese citizenship.}}It remains the longest in historical Japan{{Refnest|{{Cite web|title=日本で一番長い名字は漢字5文字のもの 一番短い名は1文字|url=https://news.livedoor.com/article/detail/8409764/|website=Livedoor News|accessdate=May 12, 2020}}}}. Its origin traces back to the [[Kadenokōji]] area in [[Heian-kyō]].{{Verification needed|Currently, one household exists in [[Yamaguchi Prefecture]]|date=August 3, 2023}} (originally of the {{ill|Kadenokōji Family (Hino lineage)|ja|勘解由小路家 (日野流)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kadenokōji Family (Hino lineage)|qq=}}, a former {{ill|Viscount|ja|子爵家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Viscount|qq=}} lineage).
Historically, families associated with the name Kadenokōji include the following:
# [[:en:Fujiwara Hok-ke|Northern Fujiwara]]: ## {{ill|Sessonji Family|ja|世尊寺家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sessonji Family|qq=}} lineage: From [[:en:Fujiwara no Koretada|Fujiwara no Koretada]], whose descendant {{ill|Keiin Sessonji|ja|世尊寺経尹|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Keiin Sessonji|qq=}} was followed by {{ill|Yukitaka Sessonji|ja|世尊寺行尹|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yukitaka Sessonji|qq=}}, who adopted the name Kadenokōji. ## {{ill|Kanshūji Lineage|ja|勧修寺流|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanshūji Lineage|qq=}}: From {{ill|Fujiwara no Tamemitsu|ja|藤原為房|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Tamemitsu|qq=}} through {{ill|Fujiwara no Tameyoshi|ja|為隆|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Tameyoshi|qq=}} to {{ill|Fujiwara no Mitsumoto|ja|光房|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Mitsumoto|qq=}} (noted as Kadenokōji). Descendant {{ill|Takakiyo Fujiwara|ja|藤原高清|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takakiyo Fujiwara|qq=}} is also listed as Kadenokōji in genealogies. ## {{ill|Hino Family|ja|日野家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hino Family|qq=}} lineage: From {{ill|Hino Sukemasa|ja|日野資長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hino Sukemasa|qq=}} through {{ill|Hino Kanemitsu|ja|藤原兼光|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hino Kanemitsu|qq=}} to {{ill|Hirohashi Yoritsugu|ja|広橋頼資|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirohashi Yoritsugu|qq=}} (noted as Kadenokōji). Yoritsugu's descendants, including {{ill|Hirohashi Tsunemitsu|ja|広橋経光|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirohashi Tsunemitsu|qq=}} and {{ill|Hirohashi Kanemoto|ja|広橋兼仲|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirohashi Kanemoto|qq=}}, later adopted the name {{ill|Hirohashi|ja|広橋家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirohashi|qq=}}. ## {{ill|Hino Family|ja|日野家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hino Family|qq=}}, {{ill|Karasumaru Lineage|ja|烏丸流|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Karasumaru Lineage|qq=}}: Refer to {{ill|Kadenokōji Family (Hino lineage)|ja|勘解由小路家 (日野流)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kadenokōji Family (Hino lineage)|qq=}}. # {{ill|Kamo Clan|ja|賀茂朝臣氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo Clan|qq=}} lineage: Refer to {{ill|Kadenokōji Family (Kamo lineage)|ja|勘解由小路家 (賀茂氏)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kadenokōji Family (Kamo lineage)|qq=}}. # [[:en:Seiwa Genji|Seiwa Genji]] lineage: Refer to {{ill|Shiba Family#Kadenokōji Bukei|ja|斯波氏#勘解由小路武衛|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiba Family#Kadenokōji Bukei|qq=}}.
